{
  "answer": "**Vratisāsana, Chapter 1**\n\nThe verse is:\n\n> [VS_11s-ab] *The liquor-seller, the insect-burner, the life-taker, the potter,*  \n> [VS_11s-cd] *and the metal-burner—these five are declared to be the outcastes. ||11||*[^1]\n\nThe commentary enumerates them verbatim as follows:\n\n> And furthermore, concerning the primary outcastes, they are five in number. It is not proper to go to their stalls, nor to rest there. Who are these five primary *caṇḍālas*? One who sells liquor, one who is a trapper, one who is a butcher, one who is a potter, and one who is a goldsmith. The places of these five, their stalls, and especially their houses, must be avoided. A *viku* may not rest in such a place, for they are worse than the eighteen *caṇḍālas*.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Vratisāsana, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-vratisasana-d0fe75/01/translation/#p-2f1d82) and [next](/works/unknown-vratisasana-d0fe75/01/translation/#p-85e30c).\n[^2]: Vratisāsana, [paragraph](/works/unknown-vratisasana-d0fe75/01/translation/#p-1235c0).",
